{"key":"processedPost-11536596","value":{"id":11536596,"first":11534089,"last":11537622,"when":1259343225,"utime":"11/27/09 07:33 PM","cleanedPost":"Quickly rising pressure doesn't harm jars.&nbsp; They're built to withstand vacuum, or in other words a higher pressure outside the jar than inside.&nbsp; I've put the stove on high to heat up the PC for decades without breaking jars.<br />One other thing that will break them is packing too tight where they're pressed up against each other.&nbsp; The jars expand slightly when hot, so if they're tight to begin with, they break.&nbsp; However, in this case, he released pressure, thus he had 15 psi in the jars and 0 psi outside the jars.&nbsp; That's a recipe for breaking nearly every time, and the fact that the bottoms broke off confirms this.&nbsp; That's the weakest part of the jar, and they're designed to have the bottoms break off rather than blowing out the side of the jar.<br />RR"}}